segments.text: with General Joe Hanover.
Today's date is 29 of July, 1980.
This is part of the project of Aggies to General.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is a test.
This is an interview with Brigadier General Joe G. Hanover.
Today is Tuesday, July 29th.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start with your upbringing and your parents.
You were born in McGregor, Texas, February 10, 1918.
Could you tell me about your father?
Well, my father was Grady Hanover, which I've taken my middle name from.
In fact, I'm a junior.
My father was a hardworking laborer in McGregor, Texas.

part owner of a cotton gin and also in a grain elevator type operation which serviced the local economy down there in McLennan County he worked hard at this gin which everybody does it is seasonal very seasonal and I don't remember a great deal about the
early years in McGregor because I left there when I was seven years old.

The cause of our leaving was my father's gin burned and he and his partner I'm sure owed a good bit of money on it and according to my father he told his partner that if he would take the assumption of the debt and take the insurance that was available and just free him that he would turn his part over to him.
And then his father lived in Wheelock, Texas, which is just north of Bryan or northeast of Bryan.
So your grandfather did.
That's right, my grandfather.
And he was getting to the point that he needed someone to help him with his farm.
He had about a 1,400-acre farm that had cattle and sharecroppers.
So my father moved to Wheelock in 1925.
to assist his father with the operation of the cattle farm and the sharecropper farming and that's how we got down back down in this area.
My father was a hard-working fellow and he raised us four children.
I'm the oldest of four.
I have two brothers and one sister and we lived on this farm for
many, many years, in fact, until I started to A&M.
My mother was a very devout Christian lady who gave all of us the loving, tender care that a mother should and provided the type of home life that you think you should grow up in.
She and my father had a very wholesome household, and we think we were very fortunate in the heritage that we had.
Now, does your heritage in Texas go way back into the 1900s or before?
Oh, yes, before that.
I mean the 1800s.
Yeah, let me.
My great-grandfather came to Texas in the 1830s from the Maine area.
His parents had migrated from England.

the name Hanover started in Germany went to England and then I guess it's my great-great-grandparents my great-great-grandfather came from England to Maine he was in the Navy in the English Navy the story is that he retired of the Navy and jumped overboard and walked ashore swam ashore or something but anyhow that up in the Maine and Massachusetts area
But he came to Texas in 1835, 1836, somewhere in the middle 1800s.
He was a surveyor, and he came this way following the railroads and doing survey work.
So where my heritage goes.
About the time of the Texas Revolution.
That's right, to the early 1800s.
Now, when you say that your mother was religious,
Was she more religious than your father?
And what religion was it?
My mother was a Baptist.
My father never really belonged to any church, per se.
He was a kind and loving father, but he just never saw fit to be a member of the church.
My mother was, but they still had a very wholesome relationship.
Could you tell me about your mother's heritage?
Yes, in fact, my mother was born at Allen Farm.
You know where Allen Farm is?
It's about 15 miles south of College Station, down in Brazos County.
The Moore brothers have big farms down there at this particular time.
But she was born right here in Brazos County, in the lower part of the county.
When she was very young, her mother and father moved to Belton, but they were in Texas.
I think her father was born here, but I'm not real sure about that.
But they had been here for a good few years.
Okay.
If your mother was religious, did religion play a large role in your upbringing?
Yes.
Some of my earliest

memories of the church my mother was a pianist she played the church yes and i've told the in fact the preacher that was our our preacher there at that in mcgregor at that time has died within the last year here in bryan and i've told him many times my early remembrance of church is laying on the bench behind the piano

because my mother put me there while she played, but my father used to say every time the doors of the church opened my mother was there, but we were all taught that we needed to be in church and Sunday school on Sunday, so my mother usually had us there.
Could you tell me about your parents' education?
My mother had
little formal education.
She was fortunate enough to go to Baylor, Mary Hardin Baylor in Belton, which was a girls' school at that time.
And I think for a year or some such thing that I'm sure finances kept her from going to school.
But somewhere down the line, she learned to play the piano and was quite a musician and taught music many years later on.
My father had
formal education of a business school which was pretty prevalent during those times back there.
He went to a business school in Waco and- Did he go to high- did he finish high school and then go to a business school?
I'm sure it was about a 10th grade high school or some such thing but they called it high school.
He finished what was available
out in the rural area which was probably in the 10th grade or some such thing and then took a business college business course so that was the extent of his formal education.
Uh could you tell me about uh how would you characterize your father I mean you say he's hard working could you continue on that thing?
Well
What kind of person was he?
He was a fellow that was very concerned about the welfare of his family.
His many years that I knew him and beginning with this work at the gin and this grain elevator in McGregor he personally was there to see that the work was being done
the employees that worked for him he was always there to be helpful and tell them what he expected.
Of course out on the farm it was basically he and we boys plus the sharecroppers who back in those days if the farm owner owned the teams and tools the sharecroppers worked on the hay.

if the sharecroppers had their own teams and tools they worked on what they called third and fourth they got a third of the cotton and a fourth of the corn a lesser amount because they I mean a more amount because they finished their own equipment but my dad was up early he uh he tried to instill in us the necessity for being
diligent and dependable and know how to work even though we were not the Red Winners.
We had our chores.
We had to bring the wood in and we had to milk the cows and we had to feed the horses and, you know, the farm type chores, but he expected us to do our part and...
He put responsibility on you early then?
He did, yes.
In fact, I started milking cows or helping milk when I was seven years old.

and uh but he gave us the chores and he wasn't one of these that stand right over you know and tell you everything to do but he'd tell you what he expected and the end product and then if you didn't get it well you know he'd talk to you but he he could be a pretty stern when he needs to be I don't remember being
punished by him very many times, but the time he did, well, you know, he didn't laugh at all.
No.
He was a disciplinarian when it came to the parents.
My mother, I guess typical of boys, they always thought their mothers were joking.
He was the authority in the family then?
Well, that's probably right.
As far as
you know, what had to be done, and if there was some law laid down, well, he was the one that did it.
My mother was kind and gentle, and she might give you a little switching of the peach limb, but that wasn't the way it was, and Daddy did it.
Yeah, right.
And you tell me about the sharecroppers that you mentioned.
How many sharecroppers did you have?
Well, I look back on it now and I really don't see how they did it.
These 1,400 acres that they had, there were probably, I'd say, 300 acres that were cultivation.
The rest of it was grass and they ran cattle on it.
But I can remember one time there were 12 families that were sharecroppers on that 300 acres.
And that sounds incredible.
I just don't know.
But a lot of them is one colored family that all seem like they must have eight or 10 children.
Think about where they all black, all the sharecroppers.
But to think about 12 families making their living on these 300 couldn't have been over 400 or 400 acres.
But I just it's just almost incredible.
My father,
operated a little commissary farm that's a little store that where they provided the beans and coffee and flour and this sort of thing and the sharecroppers reimbursed them in the fall.
and their crops were gathered.
So really it was a sort of a little store on a credit farm.
They got their staple goods there.
And there was one thing that I guess helped a little.
Most of those sharecroppers, my father would let them raise pigs or chickens or maybe raise a cow or two around their home.
So it wasn't totally from the land, I mean from the cultivation that they made their living.
so where they were enterprising sharecroppers they had an opportunity to grow a lot of what they eat.
How long did sharecroppers last?
How long did you own the farm and did they last?
Well the farm was owned clear up until 1942 and my grandfather had acquired this 1400 acres over the years by 100 acres and 200 and you know put together this
1400 acres over, I would say probably a good many years, but I know that he had owned a lot of it since the early 1900s.
So he had started acquiring it back in the 1800s and it was finally sold in 1942.
But the sharecroppers had begun to dwindle prior to their selling and he had turned most of that into grazing.
where you could just raise stock.
Why'd they do them though?
They went to town.
They went to places and got jobs.
Just the same thing that countrywide people have left the farm.
Yeah, right.
Looking for an easier life.
Must have been a tough life for those people.
And they worked hard.
Of course, they'd get up, you know, they were in the fields when daylight came.
They were in the fields to dark.
That's just what it took.
Yeah.
Could you tell me about your two brothers and one sister?
How'd you get along with them?
Well, what were their ages?
Let's start with that first, and then how'd you get along with them?
The next brother under me is two years younger than I am.
and the brother under him is five years younger than he, which is seven years younger than I am, and then her sister was four years younger than the third brother, so we were within an 11 year span.
Oh, I guess we had the usual differences the brothers did.
Generally, we got along well.
We had our little spats and arguments and whatnot.
It was real strange.
We also had a cousin, a first cousin, who was orphaned.
And my grandfather took him in to raise him.
And he was a year older than I.
And it's real strange.
We three boys
would have our arguments and differences.
But when we had arguments with the cousins, the three of us pooled together.
But we had quite an interesting upbringing.
And we had a bunch of other cousins that lived out in the rural area, and we'd get together and just have great times.
So I'd say we were average congenial and had on well.
Of course, we were all real proud when her little sister came home.
We said she was spoiled and petted and whatnot, but we had a pretty congenial family.
What happened to your two brothers?
What did they do in later life?
Well, the second oldest went to A&M for a couple three years, dropped out.
He changed courses a time or two and got behind, I guess, his other

constituents and so he dropped out and and went to work and subsequently went in the service he was an armor soldier got a battlefield commission was uh when was this during the war he was he got his battlefield commission on in December of
45, which was right in the height of the last phases of the war.
You're right.
44, of course.
December 44.
And got a battlefield commission, and shortly thereafter, he was in a tank that got three German 88 shells through it.

three of the five out of the tank were killed and he fortunately was not killed but was severely wounded and lost an eye and had shrapnel all over him and got superficial burns not you know something detrimental to him and was brought back to the states for recovery and then he subsequently went in law enforcement but as a deputy sheriff here in this county and still lives here in brian
The second brother, who was the youngest of all of us, was the first one in the service, the first one in the war.
He left high school and joined the Navy.
Really?
He got in before you did?
That's right.
That's real strange.
Yeah, that is.
Well, let me take that back.
He got in the combat area before I left.
Oh, I see.
He went in, he must have gone in in 42.
I was actually in the service, but I was in the States training soldiers.
But he had the good fortune of serving on the battleship New Jersey.

that was the flagship of Spruance and Halsey and whatnot and he was a fire control NCO or a fire control technician right and I had a very I would I would guess a very interesting World War II service of course he's in the Pacific most of the time but

service on those big battle wagons must have been much better than the dog faces laying in the trenches but he stayed in fact he went in I guess he was he was only about 17 or 18 when he went in so he was in the new on the New Jersey throughout the entire he went to I guess Norfolk or somewhere over there where it was actually built
and went on it from Shakedown Cruise.
So he was on it from its maiden voyage right on to the time he got this church out of service.
And then the sister uh what did he do later in life?
Uh he he came back to this area and uh he went in the lumber business.
Oh really?
He first traveled and sold lumber for a good many years for a big concern out of San Antonio

and then decided that he could sell to other people except himself so a number of years later he actually went into the lumber business and has his own business now and has had it for a number of years in Austin.
Oh really?
Which one is it?
It's called Hanover Lumber Company.
In Austin?
It's uh well it's out to the east of Austin but it's had a very interesting
career in the business for himself.
He has four children and three of them work with him in the business.
That's sort of interesting.
And the sister went to Texas University, got her degree and went to Corpus, I mean went to... What was her degree?
Education.
She was a school teacher.
Went down to Port Arthur.
and went into the school system down there and met a young man who was working for Guff Oil Company and they were married subsequently and she taught a year or two and then she became a housewife.
So she's continued living in Port Arthur ever since.
The youngest brother, the one who went in the Navy, never did go to college.
So there really were three of us, two of us graduated the second and had a limited amount of college work.
Now there must have been some episodes earlier in your life that you feel had sort of a significant impact on your later life or your career.
Were there?
Yes, and it's real funny I think, I hear so many people talk about
They never didn't know what they wanted to do until they actually got out of school or even halfway through college.
I had a specific college career in mind before I got out of high school.
Really?
That is unusual.
Well long before that in 1929 and at that time I was 11 years old
The Old San Antonio Road, which is the borderline between these two counties.
Are you familiar with what road that is?
It's about halfway from here to Hearn.
Is that Old Service Road or OSR now?
That's right.
The OSR.
Is that?
I've been on that road.
Is that?
That's what it is.
What is it?
OSR?
Old San Antonio Road.
Old San Antonio?
I just thought it said for Old Service Road.
Old San Antonio.
Old San Antonio Road.
It was
called in the Spanish times El Camino Real but later became what you call the old San Antonio.
It was San Antonio to Nacogdoches Trail.
Sure sure which was one of the oldest.
That's right.
In fact it's built in the 1700s.
Way back way back yeah and our home was was adjacent to that.
It followed our property for about two miles.
A little side

issue you're talking about OSR that's the only road in the state of Texas that's referred to by that type of designation every other is a number but it is OSR officially but we lived on this road in 1929 the highway department undertook to regrade it gravel it and put a surface on it in other words make a highway out of it
And I got fascinated with the survey crew that was doing the survey work on that road and said to my people and everybody, I want to be a civil engineer.
That was 11 years old.
I graduated from high school, went to A&M, enrolled in civil engineering and got a degree.
So when I was 11 years old, I said what I was going to take in college and did it.
And that's a little unusual.
And basically it was because you were stimulated right there on the road.
I followed that survey crew as far as I could walk, you know, and then come back home, but just was fascinated with them.
Why do you think that was?

Because, you know, kids see firemen who are 11 and say, gee, I'd like to be a fireman when I grow up, or they, you know, they might see an engineer crew, or they might see a number of, they might see a man in uniform and say, I'd love to be a general.
Why do you think that was?
I really don't know.
It just, just one of those things that, that the work they were doing, and then the subsequent work that followed it, building that road, I stayed out there just,
days upon the end, you know, and it was crude as compared to today's methods.
Sure.
Mule-drawn scrapers.
Were they?
Yes, sir.
Mule-drawn scrapers.
They had some mechanical tractors, I mean tractors with motors and whatnot, but most of the dirt work was done with mule-drawn scrapers, and that fascinated me.
And I knew it all started with this survey crew.
That's just the kind of thing I wanted to do.
Did you talk to any of the workers?
Oh, gosh, I was just right in their hair.
We even provided a place for them to board their mules and horses.
My father provided a corral where they could come up at night as long as they were within commuting distance, you know, long, within a three or four mile area.
He'd provide them a corral and a place for them to keep their feed and they could water and bed down their work animals at night.
And further than that,
And he provided them an area to put their tent up where they could stay.
See, they lived in tents at that time because they couldn't commute anywhere.
It was too far.
And my mother boarded these road hands, fed them for a price, you know.
She fed them for weeks at a time.
And, you know, gosh, I thought they'd made for me.
and I talked with them and lived with them and I'd go down their tent at night and we'd sit around and they'd tell me the biggest bull story, you know.
So it's just... What kind of people were they?
Just, just across the board laborers.
There were, there were, there were some whites, some blacks.
They worked an integrated crew then?
Oh yes, oh yes.
And just,
just real down-to-earth, hard-working people that were trying to make a living.
And as I say, they'd be gone from home a week at a time.
They'd come out there and stay all week, live in this tent.
My mother would feed them, and on weekends, they'd pull five of them and get them all day forward and commute back to wherever their home was and spend the day with their folks and then come back.
So I guess it just ingrained it in me, I don't know.
But the construction aspect of it just didn't seem to suit me.
It seems to me that you and your two brothers and sister all have had successful careers.
In which ways do you think that your parents are responsible for that?
Well, when I got ready to go to A&M, my father told me, he said, I do not have the financial means to send you to A&M.
See, I started in 1936, which was just coming out of the Depression.
But he said, I'll tell you what I can do.
He said, you can stay at home.
I can board you.
I can provide you with food and a place to live if you can find some way to commute back and forth.
My grandfather had an old 1929 Chevrolet.
He told me, he said, if you can get enough people to ride with you to help pay your expenses,
I was sort of mechanically inclined.
He said, I believe you could keep the old car up, and you can take that car and use it if you can commute back and forth and use it for your transportation.
Well, I did.
I got people that were interested in going back for it.
Some of them were students.
Some of them worked at A&M.
Triple A was in B&M.
That was part of the agriculture program.
And I always had a load of people that wanted to go.
And I'd gather them up in the morning after I milked seven cows, gather them up, head to A&M.
go to school all day, and I worked.
I worked for the landscape department on the grounds.
Doing anything I had to do.
I picked mealybugs off the chrysanthemums, I dug in the flowerbeds, I hauled compost out of the Calvary stables.
You know, whatever there was to do, I was ready, because I wanted to go to school.
And I got 30 cents an hour.
And I was allowed to work.
Which was above minimum wage actually.
I think it was.
It was.
The first minimum wage went in in 37 and that was only 25 cents an hour.
Well we were paid.
Well we were getting 30 at that time and I was allowed to work 40 hours a month.
A day student could work 40 hours a month.
That's right.
And that gave me $12 a month.
And that made the difference in homeschool.
Had I not gotten that $12 a month, I couldn't have made it.
Because that brought my little books and paper and pencils and whatnot.
And I owned one cow that my grandfather had given me.
She had one calf a year.
And I sold that calf in time each year to pay my $50 or whatever it was for the...
what do you call it
